  "dailyTipCategoryTip": "Tip",
  "dailyTipCategoryMyth": "Myth busted",
  "dailyTipGotIt": "Got it",
  "dailyTip_general_doms": "DOMS does not tell you whether a workout was effective. You can progress without soreness the next day.",
  "dailyTip_general_sweat": "Sweating more does not burn more fat. Sweat is water and salt; workload and calorie balance matter.",
  "dailyTip_general_sleep": "Sleeping 7–9 hours helps muscle recovery, appetite control, and performance.",
  "dailyTip_general_spot": "You cannot spot-reduce fat with ab work. Fat loss follows genetics and overall deficit.",
  "dailyTip_general_progressive": "Progressive overload — more weight, reps, or sets over time — is the foundation of improvement.",
  "dailyTip_general_bulky": "Lifting weights will not make most women look bulky overnight. Hypertrophy takes years and high volume.",
  "dailyTip_general_warmup": "5–10 minutes of specific warm-up reduces injury risk and improves working-set quality.",
  "dailyTip_general_carbs_night": "Carbs at night do not make you gain fat because of the clock. Daily calories matter most.",
  "dailyTip_general_hydration": "Even mild dehydration can hurt strength and focus. Drink water through the day, not only at the gym.",
  "dailyTip_general_stretch_cold": "Static stretching cold before heavy lifting does not beat an active movement warm-up for injury prevention.",
  "dailyTip_general_scale_daily": "Scale weight swings with water, salt, and digestion. Look at weekly trends, not one reading.",
  "dailyTip_general_meal_timing": "You do not need to eat every 3 hours to lose fat or build muscle. Daily calories and protein matter more.",
  "dailyTip_general_detox": "Your liver and kidneys already detox. Juice cleanses do not replace good nutrition and sleep.",
  "dailyTip_general_rest_days": "Rest days are not wasted time — much of training adaptation happens while you recover.",
  "dailyTip_general_form_first": "Adding load with poor technique stalls long-term progress and raises injury risk.",
  "dailyTip_general_steps": "More daily steps (NEAT) can matter as much as formal cardio for body composition.",
  "dailyTip_general_fasted_cardio": "Fasted training does not magically burn more fat. Total daily deficit still drives fat loss.",
  "dailyTip_general_bcaa": "If protein intake is already adequate, BCAAs add little. Whole meals beat isolated supplements first.",
  "dailyTip_general_creatine": "Creatine monohydrate is well studied: it often improves strength and repeated-set performance with a strong safety profile.",
  "dailyTip_general_pain_vs_soreness": "Muscle soreness is normal; sharp, stabbing, or joint pain is not. Learn the difference.",
  "dailyTip_general_consistency": "Three solid workouts per week for a year beats one perfect month you quit.",
  "dailyTip_general_track_progress": "Logging weights, reps, or times reveals progress when the mirror does not change overnight.",
  "dailyTip_general_fiber": "More fiber improves fullness and digestion. Fruit, legumes, and vegetables help you hit goals without starving.",
  "dailyTip_general_toning_machines": "Vibration toning machines do not replace progressive resistance training and solid nutrition.",
  "dailyTip_general_sweat_detox": "Sweating in a sauna or sauna suit does not remove toxins or fat — only water you regain when hydrated.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_failure": "You do not need to train to failure every set. Leaving 1–3 reps in reserve is often enough to grow.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_confusion": "Muscle confusion by changing exercises every week is not required. Consistency with progression matters more.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_protein": "Total daily protein matters more than taking it immediately post-workout.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_compounds": "Prioritize compound lifts (squat, deadlift, press) and add isolation where needed.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_volume": "Most people grow well on roughly 10–20 hard sets per muscle group per week, spread out.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_tempo": "Ultra-slow reps are not required for hypertrophy. Control the movement without sacrificing load progression.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_pump": "The pump feels great but is not the only sign of a good session. Progressive load and volume also count.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_frequency": "Training a muscle twice per week is usually more efficient than one massive session.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_eccentric": "The eccentric phase matters: lower loads with control instead of dropping the bar.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_mind_muscle": "Mind-muscle connection may help isolation work but does not replace sufficient load on heavy compounds.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_deload": "A lower-volume week every 4–8 weeks can break hypertrophy plateaus.",
  "dailyTip_hypertrophy_sleep_growth": "Much muscle recovery happens while you sleep. Shortchanging sleep slows gains even with hard training.",
  "dailyTip_strength_rest": "On heavy sets (3–6 reps), 2–4 minute rests usually beat rushing back in.",
  "dailyTip_strength_failure": "Training to failure every session is not required for strength. Technique and progressive load come first.",
  "dailyTip_strength_technique": "Adding weight while keeping form is safer and more sustainable than grinding ugly reps.",
  "dailyTip_strength_specificity": "To squat more, you need to squat heavy regularly — not only accessory work.",
  "dailyTip_strength_belt": "A lifting belt does not weaken your core when used on very heavy sets and you still train accessories without it.",
  "dailyTip_strength_warmup_sets": "Gradual warm-up sets prepare technique and the nervous system before heavy work.",
  "dailyTip_strength_cns": "Very heavy sessions fatigue the nervous system. Alternate hard days with moderate or technique days.",
  "dailyTip_strength_accessories": "Well-chosen accessories (back, triceps, core) fix weak links that limit main lifts.",
  "dailyTip_strength_1rm_test": "Testing true 1RM every week adds fatigue and risk. Use submax reps and RPE to track progress.",
  "dailyTip_strength_grip": "Weak grip can limit deadlifts and rows before back or legs fail. Training grip pays off.",
  "dailyTip_strength_leg_drive": "Leg drive and upper-back tension on bench press transfer more force than arms alone.",
  "dailyTip_strength_program_hopping": "Switching programs every two weeks stops adaptation. Give a plan time before changing.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_cardio": "Cardio helps, but strength plus a deficit preserves muscle and improves body composition.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_strength": "Keep lifting in a deficit: it helps preserve muscle mass.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_starve": "Eating too little slows progress, increases hunger, and can cost muscle.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_scale": "Water retention is normal in a cut. Trust trends, measurements, and performance — not one weigh-in.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_cheat_meal": "A cheat meal does not boost metabolism for days. It can help mentally if it fits weekly calories.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_protein": "Higher protein in a deficit reduces hunger and protects muscle. Aim around 1.6–2.2 g/kg if you can adhere.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_neat": "Walk more, take stairs, move outside the gym. Non-exercise activity adds up during a cut.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_fat_burn_zone": "The fat-burn zone burns more fat per minute but not necessarily more total fat loss if weekly output is lower.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_slow_cut": "Moderate deficits (~300–500 kcal) usually preserve more muscle and energy than aggressive cuts.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_liquids": "Sugary drinks, alcohol, and creamy coffees add calories without filling you up. Liquids are an easy win.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_steps": "Targeting 8–10k daily steps during a cut improves adherence without extra hours of cardio.",
  "dailyTip_fatloss_sleep": "Short sleep raises hunger and wrecks diet adherence. Sleep is part of the deficit plan.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_easy": "Most runs or sessions should feel conversational to build an aerobic base.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_more": "More mileage is not always better. Overtraining hurts pace and raises injury risk.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_8020": "80/20 rule: ~80% easy volume, ~20% hard. Build base without burning out.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_strength": "Leg and core strength improve running economy and reduce overload injuries.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_shoes": "Rotate shoes and avoid stacking huge mileage on one worn pair.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_hydration": "On long sessions, hydrating before and during prevents sharp pace drops from thirst or heat.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_intervals": "Well-planned intervals improve VO₂ max but do not replace easy aerobic volume.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_recovery": "Sleep, food, and hydration after long sessions matter as much as the session itself.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_taper": "Cutting volume 1–2 weeks before a key race leaves legs fresh without losing fitness.",
  "dailyTip_endurance_only_cardio": "Running only without strength can raise overuse injury risk. Include 1–2 strength sessions weekly.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_consistency": "Training 3–4 days per week consistently beats perfect cycles you quit.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_deload": "A lighter week every 4–8 weeks helps recovery and long-term progress.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_variety": "Small exercise changes each month keep motivation without trashing progression.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_microcycles": "Alternating harder and lighter weeks prevents stalls without stopping completely.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_mobility": "10 minutes of mobility 2–3 times weekly improves range and comfort — not just for yoga people.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_perfect_week": "You do not need a perfect week to stay fit. Sustainable 80% adherence is enough.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_habits": "Tie training to a fixed time or routine so skipping takes more effort than showing up.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_social": "Social meals fit maintenance: balance the day or week instead of extreme compensation fasting.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_health": "Blood pressure, daily energy, and sleep quality are valid progress markers besides scale weight.",
  "dailyTip_maintenance_enjoy": "The plan you enjoy is the one you will keep for years. Pick training you want to repeat."
